sentence: Home improvement goods retailer Home Depot ( HD ) is scheduled to report its third-quarter numbers on November 14, with the consensus calling for earnings of $1.81 per share, up from $1.60 during the same period last year.
The company will report before the market open, and shares are up 21.7% on the year.
HD was recently trading at $163.42, down $4.52 from its 12-month high and $40.50 above its 12-month low.
Technical indicators for HD are bullish and the stock is in a strong upward trend.
The stock has recent support above $162.25 and has recent resistance below $168.00.
Of the 19 analysts who cover the stock, nine rate it a "strong buy", three rate it a "buy", and seven rate it a "hold".
HD gets a score of 73 from InvestorsObserver's Stock Score Report.

Strength in the overall housing market continues to prop up home improvement stocks, and Home Depot ( HD ) has enjoyed steady gains over the last five years, and the stock is currently just shy of its all-time high.
The company has topped estimates on the top and bottom lines each of the last four quarters, and another strong quarterly report should push shares even higher.
The street expects another earnings beat, with a whisper number of $1.84 versus the $1.81 consensus.

With a P/E of 23.6, and earnings forecast to rise 13.6% this year, and an additional 13.4% next year, there is still plenty of upside potential left in the stock to warrant setting up a new position in the stock ahead of the upcoming report.
If you want to set up a bullish hedged trade on HD, consider a January 140/145 bull-put credit spread for a 30-cent credit.
That's a potential 6.4% return (33.3% annualized*) and the stock would have to fall 11.1% to cause a problem.
If you want to take a bearish stance on the stock at this time, consider a January 180/185 bear-call credit spread for a 30-cent credit.
That's a potential 6.4% return (18.5% annualized*) and the stock would have to rise 10.3% to cause a problem.
